01 Jul 2018 10:31






Hmmm trying to decipher their meaning and implications has been an interesting experience. The slow disclosure of information fits the tale perfectly, and creates a chilling sense of discovery. Yeah, I like the way this story is told.

But, in my opinion, the story itself destroys its own potential by the end. Throughout the article is established the emptiness left by a humanity that fought and lost, the destruction and recreation of all life once and once again, our end at the hands of an eldritch abomination that is so vast and so big that we can't neither defeat nor negotiate with. Nihilism, extinction, inability to avoid being devoured by the God who raised us to that purpose; these themes set a specific tone, the expectation that this story can only resolve in the most ominous way possible.

And then, everything the article has built since the beginning is destroyed to its foundations; the good Stellar Protectorate saves us all and the Foundation destroys the great, death-bringing monster. Everything so carefully established for the duration of the piece means nothing and is worth nothing, the chilling expectation of horror is never met, and instead all is replaced by a good ending completely alien to the rest of the article that is far less interesting and thought provoking. The last bit of horror is taken away when the eldritch abomination is called .

 Yeah, poor guys, we have cool FTL ships and an almighty Galactic Coalition willing to protect us :P

That's how I feel about this SCP. English is not my primary language; I apologize if something in this message sounds strange or weird.

I have to -1, but I'll be watching for the future additions author has promised. Don't get me wrong, it's a great skip, and it'll be loved by many — it's just that I don't like how the story twists.







